radiographic_examinations.findings: In the upper arch, central and lateral deciduous incisors are present, and the permanent counterparts can be seen. Small buds referring to first premolars can be observed, while the buds of the second premolar and of the first molar are not visible. There are erupted teeth similar to molars with large cubic crowns. The buds of the second and third molars are present. In the lower arch, there is substantial anterior crowding; the lateral incisors are included due to lack of adequate space for eruption. The buds of the premolars and of the first molars are absent bilaterally. The buds of the second and third molars are present distally.
